   <abstract >This study builds on prior literature that examines the importance of Black male teachers in the K-12 public education system. I began by exploring the differential attitudes of Black male teachers and the systemic, institutional, and organizational factors that contribute to their growth or stagnation within the profession. Through the lens of critical race theory, I conducted a narrative inquiry to discover Black male teachers' experiences in one school district. In an effort to bring attention to the factors, be they support systems or barriers, I acquired an understanding on what they see as critical in shaping their decision to stay in K-12 public education. I explored the extent to which the perceived notions of Black male teachers' workplace experiences differ from their actual narratives. Findings indicated there is a lack of supports specific to the needs of in place for Black male teachers in place to aid them in their career as teachers. Implications for future research is presented at the conclusion of the study.</abstract>
